{
  "doc_id": "51396",
  "text": "In the austral summer of 2010/2011, an unprecedented MHW affected about 2000 km of the western Australian coastline. During this La Niña-driven event, sea surface temperatures (SST) along the coast between 22 and 34 • S exceeded the typical summer level by 3 • C on average, including peaks of 5 • C above average at numerous sites over this range [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . The MHW was superimposed on a long term, increasing SST trend of about 0.1 • C per decade off south-western Australia [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
